#read data
countpres = read_csv('data/countypres_2000-2016.csv')
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   year = col_double(),
##   state = col_character(),
##   state_po = col_character(),
##   county = col_character(),
##   FIPS = col_double(),
##   office = col_character(),
##   candidate = col_character(),
##   party = col_character(),
##   candidatevotes = col_double(),
##   totalvotes = col_double(),
##   version = col_double()
## )
#a function to choose the proportion of the party won.
vote_win = function(y,p,s)
{
       countpres%>% filter(year==y,party==p,state_po==s) %>%
                mutate(vote_prop = 100*(candidatevotes/totalvotes)) %>%
                select(FIPS,year,state_po,county,party,vote_prop)

}

                                Unemployment_rate_2012,Unemployment_rate_2016)

us_map<-st_read("data/tl_2019_us_county.shp",stringsAsFactors=FALSE,quiet=TRUE)
tx_map = us_map %>% filter(STATEFP =='48')%>%
         rename('FIPS'='GEOID')
ca_map = us_map %>% filter(STATEFP =='06')%>%
         rename('FIPS'='GEOID')
pa_map = us_map %>% filter(STATEFP =='42')%>%
         rename('FIPS'='GEOID')
vote_tx_2008 = vote_win(2008,'republican','TX') %>%
                mutate(FIPS = as.character(FIPS))
vote_tx_2012 =vote_win(2012,'republican','TX')%>%
            mutate(FIPS = as.character(FIPS))
vote_tx_2016 = vote_win(2016,'republican','TX')%>%
            mutate(FIPS = as.character(FIPS))

tx_map1 = tx_map %>% left_join(vote_tx_2008[,c('FIPS','vote_prop')],by='FIPS')
map11 = ggplot(tx_map1) +
        geom_sf(aes(geometry=geometry,fill=vote_prop))+
        labs(title='2008 Vote proportion of Republican of Texas')+
        xlab('Longitude')+
        ylab('Latitude')+
        theme(plot.title = element_text(colour = "black", size = 14, vjust = 1,hjust = 0.5))

tx_map2 = tx_map %>% left_join(vote_tx_2012[,c('FIPS','vote_prop')],by='FIPS')

library(reticulate)
## Warning: package 'reticulate' was built under R version 4.0.3
use_python('D:/Anaconda')
os <- import("os")
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
# %matplotlib inline
import geopandas as gp
unemployment = pd.read_excel('data/Unemployment.xls',skiprows=7)
unemployment.rename(columns={'FIPStxt':'FIPS'},inplace=True)
unemployment['FIPS'] = unemployment['FIPS'].astype(str)
unemployment0 = unemployment[['FIPS','Stabr','area_name','Unemployment_rate_2008','Unemployment_rate_2012','Unemployment_rate_2016']]
us_map = gp.read_file('data/tl_2019_us_county.shp')
#for Texas
unemployment_tx =unemployment0[unemployment0['Stabr'] == 'TX'][1:]
tx_map = us_map[us_map['STATEFP']=='48']
tx_map.rename(columns={'GEOID':'FIPS'},inplace=True)
## D:\Anaconda\lib\site-packages\pandas\core\frame.py:4133: SettingWithCopyWarning: 
## A value is trying to be set on a copy of a slice from a DataFrame
## 
## See the caveats in the documentation: https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/indexing.html#returning-a-view-versus-a-copy
##   errors=errors,
map_tx = pd.merge(tx_map,unemployment_tx,on='FIPS',how='left',left_index=True, right_index=False).reset_index(drop=True)
map1 = gp.GeoDataFrame(map_tx)
#for California
unemployment_ca =unemployment0[unemployment0['Stabr'] == 'CA'][1:]
unemployment_ca['FIPS'] = '0'+unemployment_ca['FIPS']

ca_map = us_map[us_map['STATEFP']=='06']
ca_map.rename(columns={'GEOID':'FIPS'},inplace=True)

map_ca = pd.merge(ca_map,unemployment_ca,on='FIPS',how='left',left_index=True, right_index=False).reset_index(drop=True)
map2=  gp.GeoDataFrame(map_ca)
# for Pennsylvania
unemployment_pa =unemployment0[unemployment0['Stabr'] == 'PA'][1:]
pa_map = us_map[us_map['STATEFP']=='42']
pa_map.rename(columns={'GEOID':'FIPS'},inplace=True)
map_pa = pd.merge(pa_map,unemployment_pa,on='FIPS',how='left',left_index=True, right_index=False).reset_index(drop=True)
map3 = gp.GeoDataFrame(map_pa)
# the unemployment rate of 2008
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1,figsize=(12,8))
map1.plot(column= 'Unemployment_rate_2008', ax=ax, legend=True,legend_kwds={'label': "Unemployment rate"})
ax.set_title("2008 Unemployment rate of Texas", fontsize=14)
ax.set_xlabel("Longitude",fontsize=18)
ax.set_ylabel("Laititude",fontsize=18)
plt.show()


fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1,figsize=(12,8))
map2.plot(column= 'Unemployment_rate_2008', ax=ax, legend=True,legend_kwds={'label': "Unemployment rate"},cmap='plasma_r')
ax.set_title("2008 Unemployment rate of California", fontsize=20)
ax.set_xlabel("Longitude",fontsize=18)
ax.set_ylabel("Laititude",fontsize=18)
plt.show()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1,figsize=(10,8))
map3.plot(column= 'Unemployment_rate_2008', ax=ax, legend=True,legend_kwds={'label': "Unemployment rate",'orientation': "horizontal"},cmap='magma_r')
ax.set_title("2008 Unemployment rate of Pennsylvania", fontsize=20)
ax.set_xlabel("Longitude",fontsize=18)
ax.set_ylabel("Laititude",fontsize=18)
plt.show()


# the unemployment rate of 2012

plt.show()

map3.plot(column= 'Unemployment_rate_2012', ax=ax, legend=True,legend_kwds={'label': "Unemployment rate",'orientation': "horizontal"},cmap='magma_r')
ax.set_title("2012 Unemployment rate of Pennsylvania", fontsize=20)
